\begin_layout Subsection
Subthreshold resonance and resulting network responses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although population rate models may capture realistic differential oscillations
 in frequency bands that are associated with feedforward and feedback processing
, a smaller spatial scale is required to explain the frequency preferences
 of involved oscillating populations.
 In particular, a number of experimental studies has associated resonance
 at network level to subthreshold resonance of the membrane voltage of single
 neurons 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citep{Hutcheon1996a}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which also shows preferred frequencies 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citep[for a review see]{Hutcheon2000}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Biological subthreshold membrane potential resonance arises from voltage-gated
 ionic currents with slow time scales 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citep{Ulrich2002a,White1995}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 By manipulation of some variables governing the ion channels responsible
 for these slow time scales, a combined experimental and modelling study
 recently modified frequencies of network level resonance: shifting the
 peak frequency of subthreshold resonance implicitly also shifted the respective
 peak in network power spectrum
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citep[methods]{Chen2016a}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The ion channels reconfigured to achieve this shift are located on apical
 dendrites of pyramidal neurons in the cortical layer 5, which, in turn,
 are commonly associated with LFOs in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\vartheta$
\end_inset

- and lower 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

-range 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citep{Schmidt2016,Hutcheon1996}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Thus we tested whether 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

-oscillations, that did not occur the in the microcircuit 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citep{Potjans}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and multi-area model 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citep{Schmidt2015a}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 naturally, would arise when neurons with appropriately configured subthreshold
 resonance preference were introduced to the model.
 As animal studies indicated that up to 50% of the excitatory pyramidal
 population in layer 5 expresses subthreshold resonance at LFOs 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citep{Silva1991}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we used this as a ballpark number for the size of the excitatory subpopulation
 in layer 5 of the Potjans- and Schmidt-models.
 The implementation of subthreshold resonance itself was achieved by replacing
 the respective LIF-neurons in the models by 
\shape italic
generalised integrate-and-fire neurons with two membrane variables (GIF2)
\shape default
, as proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
